  "abstract": "<jats:p>\n            A moderate halophile,\n            <jats:italic>Micrococcus halobius</jats:italic>\n            ATCC 21727, produced an extracellular dextrinogenic amylase when cultivated in media containing 1 to 3 M NaCl. The amylase was purified from the culture filtrate to an electrophoretically homogenous state by glycogen-complex formation, diethylaminoethyl-cellulose chromatography, and Bio-Gel P-200 gel filtration. The enzyme had maximal activity at pH 6 to 7 in 0.25 M NaCl or 0.75 M KCl at 50 to 55Â°C. The activity was lost by dialysis against distilled water. Molecular weight was estimated to be 89,000 by sodium dodecyl sulfate-gel electrophoresis. The action pattern on amylose, soluble starch, and glycogen showed that the products were maltose, maltotriose, and maltotetraose, with lesser amount of glucose.\n          </jats:p>",
